                            <comment id="20516" author="charlesb" created="Sat, 28 Oct 2006 18:29:38 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;My original forum post: &lt;a href=&quot;http://forum.springframework.org/showthread.php?t=30820&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;http://forum.springframework.org/showthread.php?t=30820&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20555" author="gonne" created="Mon, 30 Oct 2006 22:18:03 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I have also noticed a high performance degradation from Spring 1.2.8 to Spring 2.0 with heavy use of prototype beans. I have attached a very simple test application which creates 100,000 prototype beans without multithreading and generated the following results:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Spring 1.2.8        2437ms&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0 RC1  2813ms&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0 RC2  3015ms&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0 RC3  4515ms&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0 RC4  4532ms&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0            4594ms&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Profiling shows that about 30% of each bean creation is spent in the constructor of org.springframework.beans.SimpleTypeConverter called by the constructor of org.springframework.beans.factory.support.BeanDefinitionValueResolver during ...applyPropertyValues(). Please look at the screenshot of my profiling session.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20556" author="gonne" created="Mon, 30 Oct 2006 22:18:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Simple test application&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20557" author="gonne" created="Mon, 30 Oct 2006 22:20:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Screenshot of my profiling session&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="20909" author="bayard" created="Thu, 16 Nov 2006 11:31:34 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Apart from the fact that I want Gonne&apos;s machine; I can confirm the performance issue. Using Gonne&apos;s profiling app:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Spring 1.2.7  ~9 seconds&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.0 release  ~30-&amp;gt;35 seconds&lt;br/&gt;
Spring 2.x current HEAD - ~35-&amp;gt;40 seconds&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I ran a bunch of 2.0 and 2.x&apos;s and although the numbers bounce around a fair bit, HEAD definitely seems to come out around 5 seconds slower each time. This shows that the fix for &lt;a href=&quot;https://jira.spring.io/browse/SPR-2743&quot; title=&quot;BeanFactoryUtils.beansOfTypeIncludingAncestors(ListableBeanFactory, Class) performance is an order of magnitude slower than it was in rc3&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;SPR-2743&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;SPR-2743&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt; is not having an effect here (as was postulated in the forum).&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21026" author="gonne" created="Wed, 22 Nov 2006 03:00:47 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Is it possible to change the issue type from &quot;improvement&quot; to &quot;bug&quot; ?&lt;br/&gt;
We can not use the final version in our production environment, because the load of our system would increase to much.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21116" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 29 Nov 2006 03:55:18 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;This is largely fixed in CVS HEAD now, and will be released in the next nightly 2.0.2 snapshot. Please give it an early try and let me know how it works for you! &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There were a couple of underlying problems here, one of them being the SimpleTypeConverter in BeanDefinitionValueResolver that you pointed out - which was easy enough to address. The main problem, however, was the PropertyDescriptor filtering for dependency checks, introduced in 2.0 RC3: Because of @Required and its RequiredAnnotationBeanPostProcessor, we performed the exclusion of non-eligible properties more eagerly than before. This alone caused a 15 times increase in bean creation time in a micro benchmark! I addressed this through appropriate upfront checks (avoiding it if no dependency check goes on in the first place) as well as the caching of markers for excluded PropertyDescriptors. So this remains fast even in case of active dependency checks. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The overall performance increase in my micro benchmark is about a factor of 20. Bean creation is in general still about 30% slower than with Spring 1.2.8, depending on the concrete scenario, but it&apos;s even signifcantly faster than 1.2.8 with active dependency checks now. In any case, 2.0.2 should match the performance of 2.0 RC2 again. Further optimizations, which are bound to have a less dramatic effect, are left for a future tuning session. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="21137" author="gonne" created="Thu, 30 Nov 2006 02:55:04 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Many thanks to Juergen for the fast solution! &lt;br/&gt;
With the nightly build 2.0.2-build11 my attached test application seems to be as fast as 1.2.8. &lt;br/&gt;
We are now going to test it in our production system.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
